ontal, sphenoid, ethmoid","Frontal, parietal, temporal","Frontal, temporal, ethmoid","Frontal, ethmoid, zygomatic"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior cranial fossa is formed by the \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal, sphenoid, and ethmoid\u003C/strong\u003E bones. The frontal bone forms the anterior and lateral portions, the cribriform plate of the ethmoid forms the central portion, and the lesser wings of the sphenoid form the posterior boundary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect combinations can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrontal, parietal, and occipital\u003C/strong\u003E - The parietal and occipital bones form parts of the middle and posterior cranial fossae respectively, not the anterior cranial fossa\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrontal, parietal, and temporal\u003C/strong\u003E - While the frontal bone contributes to the anterior cranial fossa, the parietal and temporal bones do not\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrontal, temporal, and ethmoid\u003C/strong\u003E - The temporal bone forms part of the middle cranial fossa, not the anterior cranial fossa\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrontal, ethmoid, and zygomatic\u003C/strong\u003E - The zygomatic bone is part of the facial skeleton and does not contribute to any cranial fossa\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior cranial fossa houses important structures including the frontal lobes of the brain and the olfactory bulbs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The anterior cranial fossa is formed by the frontal, sphenoid, and ethmoid bones.","The cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone forms the central portion of the anterior cranial fossa.","The lesser wings of the sphenoid contribute to the posterior boundary of the anterior cranial fossa."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. 